snippet: In the On Politics newsletter: Now that Mr. Biden has entered the race, we will see whether assumptions around his support, his past and his gaffes prove true.
lead_paragraph: Hi. Welcome to On Politics, your guide to the day in national politics. I’m Matt Flegenheimer, your temporary host. Lisa Lerer is on vacation, filming her own campaign video about the promise of America.

headline_main: Cheers and Fears as Joe Biden Joins the Race
headline_print_headline: Cheers and Fears as Biden Joins the Race

snippet: Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. called Anita Hill this month to express his regret over “what she endured” testifying against Justice Clarence Thomas in 1991.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Joe Biden knew Anita Hill was going to be an issue for him. So a few weeks ago, as he prepared for his presidential announcement, he reached out to her through an intermediary and arranged a telephone call, hoping to assuage her.
abstract: Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. called Anita Hill this month to express his regret over “what she endured” testifying against Justice Clarence Thomas in 1991.

headline_main: Joe Biden Expresses Regret to Anita Hill, but She Says ‘I’m Sorry’ Is Not Enough
headline_print_headline: Biden’s ‘Regret’ For Hill’s Pain Fails to Soothe
byline_original: By Sheryl Gay Stolberg and Carl Hulse

snippet: The former vice president’s announcement video was broad and oratorical. Notably absent: policy, biography, ideology.
lead_paragraph: Joseph R. Biden Jr. began his 2020 campaign on Thursday, casting it as a rescue mission for a country facing a dire threat from its elected leader, President Trump. His announcement video was a three-and-a-half minute statement of political values, and an attempt to address why a 76-year-old former vice president is now returning to the campaign trail.

headline_main: Joe Biden’s Campaign Announcement Video, Annotated

snippet: Mr. Biden is a different kind of Democrat than most of the other leading contenders: more inclined to bipartisanship and, in some cases, more moderate.
lead_paragraph: Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr., who opened his third run for the presidency on Thursday, holds political views that can look and sound similar to the priorities of many liberals, but differ on some key details. Mr. Biden, who has a longer record in politics than any other Democrat in the sprawling 2020 field, will come under close scrutiny for those differences; one liberal group, Justice Democrats, has already come out to oppose him because of “centrist” views.

headline_main: Joe Biden, Facebook, N.F.L. Draft: Your Thursday Briefing

snippet: The former vice president has stayed on the sidelines while his record has been scrutinized. His entry is sure to reshape the Democratic primary contest.
lead_paragraph: Former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. announced Thursday that he would seek the Democratic nomination to challenge President Trump in 2020, casting the election as a national emergency and asking Democrats to put the task of defeating Mr. Trump above all their other ambitions.
abstract: The former vice president has stayed on the sidelines while his record has been scrutinized. His entry is sure to reshape the Democratic primary contest.
